1. $\beta_{tw}$ is likely positive because households with two employed persons should have higher income, therefore  $\beta_{tw} > 0$.
2. $\delta_1$ is likely positive because larger households are more likely to have(i.e are positivly correlated) two earners, therefore $\mathrm{Cov}(fsize, twoearn) > 0$ and thus $\delta_1 > 0$.
3. Therefore, the bias should be positive as $\beta_{tw} > 0$ and $\delta_1 > 0$,so $\breve{\beta}_1$ is biased upward relative to the true coefficient ($\beta_1$).

For $\breve{\beta}_6$ (marr):

1. $\beta_{tw}$ is likely positive because households with two employed persons should have higher income, therefore  $\beta_{tw} > 0$.
2. $\delta_6$ is likely positive, as being married is positively corroleted with having 2 earners, as both can work, so $\mathrm{Cov}(marr, twoearn) > 0$ and thus $\delta_6 > 0$.
3. Since $\beta_{tw} > 0$ and $\delta_6 > 0$, the bias $\beta_{tw} \cdot \delta_6$ is positive, therefore $\tilde{\beta}_6$ is biased upward relative to the true $\beta_6$.

